# SummitEthic API Data Ethics Guidelines

## Overview

This document outlines the ethical considerations and practices implemented in the SummitEthic API service.

## Data Handling Principles

### 1. Data Minimization

The API adheres to strict data minimization principles:
- Only collecting data necessary for the intended functionality
- Avoiding collection of unnecessary personal information
- Implementing automatic data pruning after {{ api_data_retention_days | default(90) }} days

### 2. Data Security

All sensitive data is protected through multiple security measures:
- Data encryption in transit using TLS {{ api_tls_version | default('1.3') }}
- Data encryption at rest using {{ api_encryption_algorithm | default('AES-256-GCM') }}
- Secure key management using {{ api_key_management | default('environment variables with restricted access') }}

### 3. Privacy by Design

The API implements privacy by design principles:
- Explicit consent mechanisms for data collection
- User-accessible data export functionality
- User-controlled data deletion capabilities
- Privacy-preserving logging (no PII in logs)

### 4. Access Control

Access to API data is strictly controlled:
- Role-based access control for API endpoints
- Detailed audit logging of all sensitive data access
- Time-limited authentication tokens
- Rate limiting to prevent abuse

## Ethical Resource Usage

The API is designed to use resources efficiently and fairly:
- Caching strategies to reduce unnecessary processing
- Rate limiting to ensure fair access for all users
- Efficiency-optimized code to reduce energy consumption
- Load balancing for equitable resource distribution

## Ethical Monitoring

The following monitoring practices are in place:
- Privacy-respecting application monitoring
- Regular ethical audits of data access patterns
- Automated alerting for unusual data access
- Resource usage monitoring to detect inefficiencies

